TY  - JOUR
T1  - Repo Runs: Evidence from the Tri-Party Repo Market
AU  - COPELAND, ADAM
AU  - MARTIN, ANTOINE
AU  - WALKER, MICHAEL
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12205
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2343
EP  - 2380
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12205
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT The repo market has been viewed as a potential source of financial instability since the 2007 to 2009 financial crisis, based in part on findings that margins increased sharply in a segment of this market. This paper provides evidence suggesting that there was no system-wide run on repo. Using confidential data on tri-party repo, a major segment of this market, we show that, the level of margins and the amount of funding were surprisingly stable for most borrowers during the crisis. However, we also document a sharp decline in the tri-party repo funding of Lehman in September 2008.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sizing Up Repo
AU  - KRISHNAMURTHY, ARVIND
AU  - NAGEL, STEFAN
AU  - ORLOV, DMITRY
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12168
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2381
EP  - 2417
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12168
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT To understand which short-term debt markets experienced ?runs? during the financial crisis, we analyze a novel data set of repurchase agreements (repo), that is, loans between nonbank cash lenders and dealer banks collateralized with securities. Consistent with a run, repo volume backed by private asset-backed securities falls to near zero in the crisis. However, the reduction is only $182 billion, which is small relative to the stock of private asset-backed securities as well as the contraction in asset-backed commercial paper. While the repo contraction is small in aggregate, it disproportionately affected a few dealer banks.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Cross-Section of Credit Risk Premia and Equity Returns
AU  - FRIEWALD, NILS
AU  - WAGNER, CHRISTIAN
AU  - ZECHNER, JOSEF
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12143
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2419
EP  - 2469
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12143
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We explore the link between a firm's stock returns and credit risk using a simple insight from structural models following Merton (): risk premia on equity and credit instruments are related because all claims on assets must earn the same compensation per unit of risk. Consistent with theory, we find that firms' stock returns increase with credit risk premia estimated from CDS spreads. Credit risk premia contain information not captured by physical or risk-neutral default probabilities alone. This sheds new light on the ?distress puzzle??the lack of a positive relation between equity returns and default probabilities?reported in previous studies.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Volatility, the Macroeconomy, and Asset Prices
AU  - BANSAL, RAVI
AU  - KIKU, DANA
AU  - SHALIASTOVICH, IVAN
AU  - YARON, AMIR
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12110
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2471
EP  - 2511
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12110
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT How important are volatility fluctuations for asset prices and the macroeconomy? We find that an increase in macroeconomic volatility is associated with an increase in discount rates and a decline in consumption. We develop a framework in which cash flow, discount rate, and volatility risks determine risk premia and show that volatility plays a significant role in explaining the joint dynamics of returns to human capital and equity. Volatility risk carries a sizable positive risk premium and helps account for the cross section of expected returns. Our evidence demonstrates that volatility is important for understanding expected returns and macroeconomic fluctuations.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Strategic and Financial Bidders in Takeover Auctions
AU  - GORBENKO, ALEXANDER  S.
AU  - MALENKO, ANDREY
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12194
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2513
EP  - 2555
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12194
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Using data on auctions of companies, we estimate valuations (maximum willingness to pay) of strategic and financial bidders from their bids. We find that a typical target is valued higher by strategic bidders. However, 22.4% of targets in our sample are valued higher by financial bidders. These are mature, poorly performing companies. We also find that (i) valuations of different strategic bidders are more dispersed and (ii) valuations of financial bidders are correlated with aggregate economic conditions. Our results suggest that different targets appeal to different types of bidders, rather than that strategic bidders always value targets more because of synergies.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Financial Intermediaries and the Cross-Section of Asset Returns
AU  - ADRIAN, TOBIAS
AU  - ETULA, ERKKO
AU  - MUIR, TYLER
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12189
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2557
EP  - 2596
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12189
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Financial intermediaries trade frequently in many markets using sophisticated models. Their marginal value of wealth should therefore provide a more informative stochastic discount factor (SDF) than that of a representative consumer. Guided by theory, we use shocks to the leverage of securities broker-dealers to construct an intermediary SDF. Intuitively, deteriorating funding conditions are associated with deleveraging and high marginal value of wealth. Our single-factor model prices size, book-to-market, momentum, and bond portfolios with an R2 of 77% and an average annual pricing error of 1%?performing as well as standard multifactor benchmarks designed to price these assets.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Global Crisis and Equity Market Contagion
AU  - BEKAERT, GEERT
AU  - EHRMANN, MICHAEL
AU  - FRATZSCHER, MARCEL
AU  - MEHL, ARNAUD
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12203
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2597
EP  - 2649
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12203
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We analyze the transmission of the 2007 to 2009 financial crisis to 415 country-industry equity portfolios. We use a factor model to predict crisis returns, defining unexplained increases in factor loadings and residual correlations as indicative of contagion. While we find evidence of contagion from the United States and the global financial sector, the effects are small. By contrast, there has been substantial contagion from domestic markets to individual domestic portfolios, with its severity inversely related to the quality of countries? economic fundamentals. This confirms the ?wake-up call? hypothesis, with markets focusing more on country-specific characteristics during the crisis.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Real Product Market Impact of Mergers
AU  - SHEEN, ALBERT
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12200
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2651
EP  - 2688
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12200
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT I document sources of value creation in mergers by analyzing novel data on the quality and price of goods sold by merging firms. When two competitors in a product market merge, their products converge in quality, and prices fall relative to the competition. These effects take two to three years to be fully realized and are stronger in mature industries. Prices do not fall, however, when the acquirer is diversifying into a new product market. This direct evidence of real changes induced by merger activity is consistent with consolidation by related merging firms to achieve operational efficiencies and lower costs.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Pyrrhic Victory? Bank Bailouts and Sovereign Credit Risk
AU  - ACHARYA, VIRAL
AU  - DRECHSLER, ITAMAR
AU  - SCHNABL, PHILIPP
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12206
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2689
EP  - 2739
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12206
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We model a loop between sovereign and bank credit risk. A distressed financial sector induces government bailouts, whose cost increases sovereign credit risk. Increased sovereign credit risk in turn weakens the financial sector by eroding the value of its government guarantees and bond holdings. Using credit default swap (CDS) rates on European sovereigns and banks, we show that bailouts triggered the rise of sovereign credit risk in 2008. We document that post-bailout changes in sovereign CDS explain changes in bank CDS even after controlling for aggregate and bank-level determinants of credit spreads, confirming the sovereign-bank loop.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Investment-Based Corporate Bond Pricing
AU  - KUEHN, LARS-ALEXANDER
AU  - SCHMID, LUKAS
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12204
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2741
EP  - 2776
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12204
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT A standard assumption of structural models of default is that firms' assets evolve exogenously. In this paper, we examine the importance of accounting for investment options in models of credit risk. In the presence of financing and investment frictions, firm-level variables that proxy for asset composition are significant determinants of credit spreads beyond leverage and asset volatility, because they capture the systematic risk of firms' assets. Cross-sectional studies of credit spreads that fail to control for the interdependence of leverage and investment decisions are unlikely to be very informative. Such frictions also give rise to a realistic term structure of credit spreads in a production economy.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Duration of Executive Compensation
AU  - GOPALAN, RADHAKRISHNAN
AU  - MILBOURN, TODD
AU  - SONG, FENGHUA
AU  - THAKOR, ANJAN V.
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12085
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - THE JOURNAL OF FINANCE
SP  - 2777
EP  - 2817
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12085
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Extensive discussions on the inefficiencies of ?short-termism? in executive compensation notwithstanding, little is known empirically about the extent of such short-termism. We develop a novel measure of executive pay duration that reflects the vesting periods of different pay components, thereby quantifying the extent to which compensation is short-term. We calculate pay duration in various industries and document its correlation with firm characteristics. Pay duration is longer in firms with more growth opportunities, more long-term assets, greater R&D intensity, lower risk, and better recent stock performance. Longer CEO pay duration is negatively related to the extent of earnings-increasing accruals.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Incentives and Endogenous Risk Taking: A Structural View on Hedge Fund Alphas
AU  - BURASCHI, ANDREA
AU  - KOSOWSKI, ROBERT
AU  - SRITRAKUL, WORRAWAT
Y1  - 2014/12/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12167
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2819
EP  - 2870
VL  - 69
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12167
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Hedge fund managers are subject to several nonlinear incentives: performance fee options (call); equity investors' redemption options (put); and prime broker contracts allowing for forced deleverage (put). The interaction of these option-like incentives affects optimal leverage ex ante, depending on the distance of fund-value from the high-water mark. We study how these endogenous effects influence performance measures used in the literature. We show that reduced-form measures that do not account for these features are subject to economically significant false discovery biases. The result is stronger for low-quality funds. We propose an alternative structural methodology for conducting performance attribution in hedge funds.
ER  - 

